  "doc_id": "14258",
  "text": "Intronic RNA and other non-protein-coding RNAs now constitute the majority of genomic output in complex eukaryotes. Moreover, after accounting for variable amounts of repetitive DNA, there is a good correlation between intron density and developmental complexity [CITATION_1] ). Introns and other noncoding RNAs have high sequence complexity and, in some cases, show interesting patterns of conservation across large evolutionary distances. Conservation is often found in large blocks that are indicative of selective constraints [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] . The fact that most introns are less conserved than their associated protein-coding exons does not mean that they lack function, but rather that they are subject to less severe constraints.",
